	var comments={
			1527: {
				id_comment: 1527,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "Cf. Rom. 10.16."
			},
					1528: {
				id_comment: 1528,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "‘Unregarded as’; in the original, simply ‘like’, but this sense appears most probable, in view of what follows. The second part of the verse may also be interpreted as meaning, ‘there is no stateliness, no majesty here to catch our eyes, no beauty to win our hearts’."
			},
					1529: {
				id_comment: 1529,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "Literally, ‘his face was as it were hidden’. In the Hebrew text, it is not clear whether the face of the Servant is hidden from the onlookers, or theirs (in disgust) from him."
			},
					1530: {
				id_comment: 1530,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "Mt. 8.17."
			},
					1531: {
				id_comment: 1531,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "Literally, according to the Latin version, ‘He has been offered up because he himself willed it’. The meaning of the Hebrew text seems to be rather, ‘he has been cruelly treated, and all the while he abased himself’."
			},
					1532: {
				id_comment: 1532,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "The beginning of this verse in the Hebrew text runs literally, ‘He was taken away from the restraint and from judgement, and his generation—who will meditate?’ The meaning usually given to the passage uses almost every word in a strange sense, and it seems probable that there has been a corruption in the text; cf. the Septuagint Greek version, quoted in Ac. 8.33."
			},
					1533: {
				id_comment: 1533,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "The Hebrew text here yields a more simple translation, ‘He (God) gave him burial with the wicked, and with the rich (man) in his death’; but the bearing of the phrase is difficult to determine. The Latin can only be interpreted (on the lines of verse 3 above) as meaning that the Servant renounced all fellowship with the wicked and the rich in order to win himself a felon’s grave."
			},
			};
</script>
